items.title: Point Spread
items.description: The number of points a team is expected to win or lose by. If the Patriots are 7.5-point favorites and you bet on them, NE needs to win by 8 or more for you to win.

items.title: Favorites vs. Underdogs
items.description: The favorite is the team that is expected to win the game, while the underdog is expected to lose. If the game is a toss-up, books will open it as a ‚Äúpick‚Äù or ‚Äúpick‚Äôem.‚Äù

items.title: Over/Under
items.description: The refers to the total amount of points/goals/runs expected to be scored in a game. You can either bet that a game will go "over" or "under" the listed total.

items.title: Moneyline Odds
items.description: A moneyline of -200 means a $200 bet would profit $100, while +350 means betting $100 would win $350. This type of bet only requires your team to win straight-up.

items.title: Public Bet % vs Money %
items.description: Public bet data represents the percentage of betting tickets to take a specific side, while money percentage indicates how much actual cash is being wagered on each side.

items.title: Open vs. Current Odds
items.description: Opening odds indicate where bookmakers set the line when they initially started taking bets. Compare the opener to the current line to see how the odds have moved.

items.title: What is a Parlay?
items.description: Parlays allow you to combine multiple wagers into one bet. It often comes with a much higher payout, but every side in the parlay must win for the overall bet to cash.

items.title: What is a Teaser?
items.description: Teasers are similar to parlays, but you're allowed to move the line for the bets you select. Every side in the teaser must win for the overall bet to cash.

items.title: What is a Unit?
items.description: A "normal" bet amount for an individual bettor. So if you typically bet $50 per game, a standard 1-unit bet for you would be $50.

systems.name: Fade Covering Teams (PRO)
systems.theory: Teams that are frequently covering by a large amount will be highly respected in the market. The public will also fall in love with these teams. When books adjust, the lines figure to be inflated and these teams should statistically regress towards the mean.
